<handout xml:id="handout-section-7-3-constrained-optimization">
  <title>7.3 Constrained Optimization</title>

  <page xml:id="p-7-3-overview">
    <title>Overview</title>

    <objectives xml:id="obj-7-3-topics-goals">
      <title>Topics</title>
      <ul>
        <li>Constrained optimization as an eigenvalue problem</li>
        <li>Distance and orthogonality constraints</li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <objectives>
      <title>Goals</title>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Apply eigenvalues and eigenvectors to solve optimization problems
          subject to distance and orthogonality constraints.
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p><nbsp/></p>


    <example xml:id="ex-7-3-unit-sphere" workspace="true">
      <statement workspace="true">
        <p>
          Consider the quadratic form <me>Q(\vec x)=9x_1^2 + 4x_2^2 + 3x_3^2</me>. Find the <em>largest</em> and <em>smallest</em> values of <m>Q(\vec x)</m> under the constraint that <m>\|\vec x\| = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <image source="./sphere73.png" xml:id="img-7-3-sphere" width="50%">
        <shortdescription>A coloring of the unit sphere which represents the values of Q from the previous example, where blue means low values and red means high values.</shortdescription>
    </image>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-3-constrained-problem">
    <title>A Constrained Optimization Problem</title>

    <p>
      Suppose we wish to find the maximum and minimum values of
    </p>
    <me>
      Q(\vec x)=\vec x^{\,T}A\vec x
    </me>
    <p>
      subject to the constraint <m>\|\vec x\|=1</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      That is, we want
    </p>
    <me>
      m=\min\{Q(\vec x)\mid \|\vec x\|=1\},\qquad
      M=\max\{Q(\vec x)\mid \|\vec x\|=1\}.
    </me>

    <p>
      This is an example of a <term>constrained optimization</term> problem.
      We are also interested in where these extreme values are attained.
    </p>
    <p>
        These problems are straight-forward when <m>Q(\vec x)</m> has no cross-product terms. What about when it does have cross-product terms?
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-7-3-example2" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the maximum and minimum values of
        </p>
        <me>
          Q(\vec x)=x_2^2 + 2x_1x_3.
        </me>
        <p>
          where <m>\vec x\in\mathbb{R}^3</m> and <m>\|\vec x\|=1</m>.
          Identify the points where these values are obtained.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
</page>

<page>

    <p>
      The image below is the unit sphere whose surface is colored according to the quadratic form from <xref ref="ex-7-3-example2"/>. Notice the agreement between our solution and the image.
    </p>

    <image source="./sphere73example2.png" xml:id="img-7-3-sphere2" width="50%" >
        <shortdescription>A coloring of the unit sphere which represents the values of Q from the previous example, where blue means low values and red means high values.</shortdescription>
    </image>



    <p><nbsp/></p>

    <title>Constrained Optimization and Eigenvalues</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-constrained-eigs">
      <title>Extrema via Eigenvalues</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>Q(\vec x)=\vec x^{\,T}A\vec x</m>, where <m>A</m> is a real symmetric
          <m>n\times n</m> matrix with eigenvalues
        </p>
        <me>
          \lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \ge \cdots \ge \lambda_n
        </me>
        <p>
          and corresponding <em>normalized</em> eigenvectors
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec u_1,\vec u_2,\ldots,\vec u_n.
        </me>
        <p>
          Under the constraint <m>\|\vec x\|=1</m>:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The <em>maximum</em> value of <m>Q</m> is <m>\lambda_1</m>,
            attained at <m>\vec x=\pm\vec u_1</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The <em>minimum</em> value of <m>Q</m> is <m>\lambda_n</m>,
            attained at <m>\vec x=\pm\vec u_n</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </statement>
    </theorem>

    <example xml:id="ex-7-3-example4" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the maximum value of <m>Q(\vec x)=\vec x^{\,T}A\vec x</m>,
          with <m>\vec x\in\mathbb{R}^3</m>, subject to the constraint
          <m>\|\vec x\|=5</m>.
          Identify a point where this maximum is obtained.
        </p>
        <me>
          Q(\vec x)=x_2^2 + 2x_1x_3.
        </me>
      </statement>
    </example>

    <p><nbsp/></p>
  </page>


  <page xml:id="p-7-3-orth-constraint">
    <title>An Orthogonality Constraint</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-orth-constraint" workspace="0.3in">
      <title>Extrema with an Orthogonality Condition</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>Q(\vec x)=\vec x^{\,T}A\vec x</m>, where <m>A</m> is a real symmetric
          <m>n\times n</m> matrix with eigenvalues
        </p>
        <me>
          \lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \ge \cdots \ge \lambda_n
        </me>
        <p>
          and corresponding eigenvectors
        </p>
        <me>
          \vec u_1,\vec u_2,\ldots,\vec u_n.
        </me>
        <p>
          Subject to the constraints
          <m>\|\vec x\|=1</m> and <m>\vec x\cdot\vec u_1=0</m>:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            The <em>maximum</em> value of <m>Q</m> is <m>\lambda_2</m>,
            attained at an eigenvector associated to <m>\lambda_2</m>.
          </li>
          <li>
            The <em>minimum</em> value of <m>Q</m> is <m>\lambda_n</m>,
            attained at <m>\vec u_n</m>.
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Here <m>\lambda_2</m> denotes the <em>second largest</em> eigenvalue of <m>A</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </theorem>


    <example xml:id="ex-7-3-example3" workspace="true">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the maximum and minimum values of <me>Q(\vec x)=\vec x^T A \vec x = x_1^2 + x_2^2 + x_3^2 + 6x_1x_2</me>,
          with <m>\vec x\in\mathbb{R}^3</m>, subject to
          <m>\|\vec x\|=1</m> and <m>\vec x\cdot\vec u_1=0</m>, where <me>A = \begin{bmatrix} 1 \amp 3 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\ 0 \amp 0 \amp 1 \end{bmatrix} \quad \text{and} \quad \vec u_1=\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\\0\end{bmatrix}</me>. Identifu points where the maximum and minimum values occur. The eigenvalues of <m>A</m> are <m>\lambda = 4, 1, -2</m>.
          </p>
      </statement>
    </example>
  </page>

</handout>